BY F. W. MAITLAND‚ LLD.

AMONG the historical materiale which have descended to us from the English monasteries this Liber Memoran- domm seems to bear an almost unique character, and to this we may, at least in part, ascribe the fact that it remained unprinted until the present year. Clearly it is no Chronicle.

Nor again can we include it in the class oi Annals. We should have ‘seit that iteras not quite in its right place had

Dr Luard comprised it in his admirable edition along with the boolrs that come to us from Dunstable, Tewkesbury, Waverley and elsewhere. Nor again can we describe it as a Cartulary. On theone hand we have not here the work oi a man who year by year sets down those events, those donations, those oppressione, those law-suits, which affected the fortunes ol the house; and on the other hand we have not a systematic collection of documents oi title, oi leoli· ments, releases and bonds, arranged according toa chrono- logical or geographical scheme. The title Liber Memo- raedorum, whenever it may have been bestowed, seems aptly to describe the book that is now in our hands. Towards the end of Edward I's reign some canon oi the house, with a good many documents before him, sat himself down to put in writing what he thought to be things worthy oi remem- brance. His selection is governed by thoughts ol the future. These acts and deeds are memorable because they may enable the priory to eniorce its claims and to resist any unjust pietensions ol its neighbours, its lords and its tenants.
